# PyMS Config Deploy Command Generator

When the user wants to deploy config changes for a pyms service, generate the exact kubectl commands they can copy-paste on the prod bastion. No git or python needed on prod.

## Steps

1. Read the values.yaml file the user provides
2. Extract all keys under `configuration.data` (e.g. `configuration.toml`, `gunicorn.py`, `logging.config`)
3. For each key, base64-encode the content
4. Generate a single `kubectl patch secret` command with all the encoded values
5. Output ready-to-paste kubectl commands

## Output Format

Always output the commands in this format:

```bash
# === Hot deploy for pyms-<service> ===
# Generated from: <values.yaml path>
# Changed keys: <list>

# Step 1: Patch Secret
kubectl patch secret pyms-<service> -n pyms -p '{"data":{"configuration.toml":"<base64>", ...}}'

# Step 2: Verify
kubectl get secret pyms-<service> -n pyms -o jsonpath='{.data.configuration\.toml}' | base64 -d | grep -A3 <relevant_section>

# Step 3: Reload pods using pyms-reload.sh
#   SIGHUP (config-only):   bash pyms-reload.sh <service>
#   Argo restart:            bash pyms-reload.sh <service> --restart
```

## Rules

- Base64-encode with NO line wraps (base64 -w0 equivalent)
- Never include secrets/passwords in the explanation text, only in the encoded patch command
- Always include a verify step so the user can confirm the patch took
- Always tell the user which keys changed and why SIGHUP vs restart was chosen
- If the user hasn't specified what changed, ask them or diff against the current branch
